##Input &gt; 0: Derivative is $1$ (gradient passes through).Input $\le$ 0: Derivative is $0$ (gradient is blocked).
## Lets define the NN Class
\[\frac{\partial Loss}{\partial z_2} = \underbrace{\frac{\partial Loss}{\partial a_2}}_{\text{Loss Gradient}} \times \underbrace{\frac{\partial a_2}{\partial z_2}}_{\text{Sigmoid Derivative}}\]\[\frac{\partial Loss}{\partial z_2} = \left( \frac{a_2 - y}{a_2(1 - a_2)} \right) \times \left( a_2(1 - a_2) \right)\]

Chain Rule for \(w_2\)
\[
\frac{\partial \text{Loss}}{\partial w_2} =
\underbrace{\frac{\partial \text{Loss}}{\partial a_2}}_{\text{Loss Gradient}}
\cdot
\underbrace{\frac{\partial a_2}{\partial z_2}}_{\text{Sigmoid Derivative}}
\cdot
\underbrace{\frac{\partial z_2}{\partial w_2}}_{\text{Hidden Input}}
\]

Plugging in the Values
\[
\frac{\partial \text{Loss}}{\partial w_2} =
\underbrace{\left( \frac{a_2 - y}{a_2(1 - a_2)} \right)}_{\text{Error}}
\cdot
\underbrace{\left( a_2(1 - a_2) \right)}_{\text{Sigmoid Slope}}
\cdot
\underbrace{a_1}_{\text{The Signal}}
\]
